        <h2 class="oj-pt0-important">The learning philosophy of your organisation</h2>
        <p>
                A learning philosophy is a statement or set of
                <strong>statements</strong> that identify an organisations
                <strong>beliefs</strong>, <strong>norms</strong> and
                <strong>values</strong> regarding <strong>teaching</strong> and
                <strong>learning</strong>. These statements influence how students are
                taught, what behaviours are expected of instructors and trainees, and
                more importantly the implicit and explicit values that the
                organisation expresses with regard to learning.
            </p>

      </div>

      <div class="oj-hero"></div>

      <div class="ians-column">

        <p>
                Very few ANSPs have an explicit learning philosophy statement, this
                does not however mean that they don’t have a learning philosophy that
                has over the years become part of the instructing culture.
            </p>

        <p>
                It could be very helpful to consider what philosophy
                <strong>your own organisation</strong> has to learning. Complete the
                following table to get a broad overview of what influences the
                learning environment you work in (of course it is possible that your
                ANSP sits somewhere in between the statements below):
            </p>

        <p class="ians-text-instruction">
                Answer the questions below. Use the notes text boxes below questions
                to record any useful thoughts you have when considering the questions.
                Your answers should be saved to your device for future visits to this
                page. You can print out your answers to keep for later reference or forward to others in your organisation. Select the button below to clear your
                saved data.
            </p>

        <button id="clearAllMemory">Clear saved answers</button>
        <button id="printAnswers" >Print my answers</button>

